A '''laryngeal cleft''' or '''laryngotracheoesophageal cleft''' is a rare [[congenital]] abnormality in the [[Posterior (anatomy)|posterior]] [[larynx|laryngo]]-[[Vertebrate trachea|trachea]]l wall.<ref>{{Cite journal
  | last = Thornton
  | first = M.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = H. Rowley, B. J. Conlon and J. D. Russell
  | title = Type I laryngeal cleft: late presentation
  | journal = Journal of Laryngology & Otology
  | volume = 115
  | issue = 10
  | pages = 821–822
  | year = 2001
  | doi = 10.1258/0022215011909053
  | pmid = 11667997
  | accessdate =8 March 2010 }}
</ref> It occurs in approximately 1 in 10,000 to 20,000 births.<ref>{{Cite journal
  | last = Pezzettigotta
  | first = S. M.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = Leboulanger N., Roger G., Denoyelle F., Garabédian E. N.
  | title = Laryngeal cleft
  | journal = Otolaryngologic Clinics of North America
  | volume = 41
  | issue = 5
  | pages = 913–33, ix
  | date = October 2008
  | pmid=18775342
  | doi = 10.1016/j.otc.2008.04.010
  | accessdate =8 March 2010 }}
</ref> It means there is a gap between the [[oesophagus]] and trachea, which allows food or fluid to pass into the airway.<ref name=Cherry>{{Cite book
