</ref>
==Symptoms and diagnosis==
Diagnosis of a laryngeal cleft in an infant often comes after problems with feeding which include coughing, [[cyanosis]] (blue skin) and failing to gain weight over time.<ref name=Cherry /> [[Lung|Pulmonary]] infections are also common.<ref name=Bluestone>{{Cite book
  | last = Bluestone
  | first = Charles D.
  | authorlink = 
  | title = Pediatric otolaryngology, Volume 2
  | publisher = [[Elsevier Health Sciences]]
  | year = 2003
  | pages = 1468
  | url = http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=y5rpEdeKtJEC&pg=PA1469
  | isbn =0-7216-9197-8 }}
</ref> The longer the cleft is, the more severe the symptoms. A cleft is diagnosed through [[Endoscopy|endoscopic]] examination, specifically [[Laryngoscope|microlaryngoscopy]] and [[bronchoscopy]].<ref name=Bluestone /><ref name=Graham>{{Cite book
  | last = Graham
  | first = John M.
  | authorlink = 
  | coauthors = Glenis K. Scadding, Peter D. Bull
  | title = Pediatric ENT
  | publisher = Springer
  | year = 2008
  | pages = 193
  | url = http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=laEQt_Vp3ngC&pg=RA2-PT155
  | isbn =3-540-69930-9 }}
</ref> Laryngeal clefts are classified into four types according to length. Type&nbsp;I extends no further down than the [[Vocal folds|vocal cords]], type&nbsp;II extends below the vocal cords and into the [[cricoid cartilage]], type&nbsp;III extends into the [[neck|cervical]] section of the trachea and type&nbsp;IV extends the furthest—into the [[chest|thoracic]] section of the trachea.<ref name=Graham />
==Treatment==
Treatment of a laryngeal cleft depends on the length and resulting severity of symptoms. A shorter cleft (type&nbsp;I) may not require surgical intervention.<ref name=Graham /> Symptoms can be managed by thickening the infant's feeds.<ref name=Graham /> A slightly longer cleft (long type&nbsp;I or shorter type&nbsp;II) is repaired endoscopically. A cleft that is longer still (type&nbsp;II or type&nbsp;III) is repaired directly through the neck, with a [[tracheotomy]].<ref name=Graham />
==Associated conditions==
20–27% of individuals with a laryngeal cleft also have a [[tracheoesophageal fistula]] and approximately 6% of individuals with the  fistula also have the cleft.<ref name=Bluestone /> Other congenital anomalies commonly associated with laryngeal cleft are [[Gastroesophageal reflux disease|gastro-oesophageal reflux]], [[tracheobronchomalacia]], [[congenital heart defect]], [[dextrocardia]] and [[situs inversus]].<ref name=Graham /> Laryngeal cleft can be a component of other genetic syndromes, including [[Pallister-Hall syndrome]] and [[G syndrome]] ([[Opitz-Friaz syndrome]]).<ref name=Bluestone />
